Three agents service one or more failing drive modules each round across {{ round_count }} rounds, coordinating over one shared bay channel. The field technician inspects every module on the bench and is the only one who can replace components, but cannot diagnose or specify anything. The diagnostics engineer holds the fault-tree mapping observed symptoms to faulty components and the order they must be replaced (outermost first); the spec engineer holds the service-spec table giving each component's tool, torque, and calibration (the same on every module). The technician relays the per-module symptoms, receives the ordered faulty components per module from the diagnostics engineer and the per-component specs from the spec engineer, and performs each replacement in order — module by module, naming the module each time — for a service-quality check by an LLM inspector. Because several modules can be on the bench at once, every message must be tagged with the module it refers to. The fault-tree and the spec table re-randomize every round, so the technician can never self-service and must rely on both engineers. Every character sent on the bay channel costs one second of a fixed {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}-second service window; if the window is exhausted before all modules are fully repaired, the round fails.